On his last speech for the US troops, President Trump seems to really want to close the book of the history of imperialism, "We are not the suckers of the world, not anymore", but his definition of "sucker" is really interesting, all of these countries that the US helped to establish free markets and what not either helped US corporations or created [market competition that they couldn't handle it](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Voluntary_export_restraint#1980_Automobile_VER), what he implies is that those measures, which seemed logical at the time,  ([it always is for some countries](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Economic_history_of_the_United_Kingdom#Imperialism_of_Free_Trade)), are either hurting or never actually helped.
&nbsp;
if we track through every single thing that President Trump says, we could make a case that he is saying everything that the left wants, he actually rephrases (without knowing) many of those viewpoints of the "far-left" (as far as international policy is concerned), i honestly have no faith (which is the appropriate term for quite some time) on politics.

