@caryoscelus: 
the theological part was the point of the text, i forgot to say that what i was mostly referring to was the attack on the possibility of freedom from different philosophical perspectives.

&nbsp;

did he substantialized "nothing"? he gave no essence and nothing to take from, only to add, which was freedom's side effects.

&nbsp;

yes, today we would simply call freedom of will. 
>...which he explores and solves only exist so far as there is one determinable ethical path. And i don't think that the word "freedom" should be burdened with his second meaning these days;
&nbsp;
the ethical path was mostly derived from Christianity, good and truth, what he added however was that the first kind of freedom, which is elementary to the second, was the way in which we act upon nothingness is meaningless and eventually hurtful, however with truth, and truth alone may lead to authoritarianism requiring freedom of will and the act of good and even evil to not be authoritarian (the first kind).
&nbsp;
so, there is a dialectic between the two kinds. also his point about the first kind and the contradiction with scarcity is very much observable.
&nbsp;
and that is mostly what i find it useful to talk about freedom (in some contexts), to have an environment where freedom takes place (the nothingness) and therefore to have rational freedom, to have freedom not for the sake of having it but to liberate ourselves rationally in the process.

at least we can go back to those kinds of synthesis without solely talking about freedom in the abstract.

@caryoscelus: just the one ;)

i should also mentioned the existential part of the argument, the nothingness from which things came, which i completely ignored here (Berdyaev doesn't entirely). 
&nbsp;
i'm not ignoring however the debate of metaphysics altogether, its large and largely divided, there is a version of metaphysics that sees objects as purely abstract.
&nbsp;
there is one real world connection tho, which is the real scarcity of things when we discuss freedom, to which i only take a dialectical approach for rationality to be used in conjunction with the possibilities of freedom to choose a path of certain freedom defined by whatever ideology you want to use with it.

@caryoscelus: 
>This has some psychology term, i'm sure, but can't remember what that was.

>PS: warning: while i'm trying to use appropriate terms, i'm not sure they are being used in the same way consistently

that should be the proper way of doing things (we are not on the 19th century anymore :D)
&nbsp;
i don't like getting into the issue of determinism because its useless (even if modern science can make a compelling case for it). the basis of this argument of rational freedom is rooted in a soft version of determinism (the replicability of the real world science and man's dialectical relation to it, its one organ).
&nbsp;
as i mentioned earlier, even if we know for a fact that determinism is correct, ought we act like that (conduct our lives)? can we? any questioning is useless because its determined by definition.
&nbsp;
the issue of involving psychology, its whole application, is that it likes to get into the idea of subject.
&nbsp;
its a good idea that you mentioned about terminology, i haven't been using it consistently at all lol, at least one term its good to clarify, that of 'subject', which i don't see as in the relation subject-object but of a whole (nature) with man being part of it and having an organic relation (same as Berdyaev), but i had to convey my meaning in popular terms by defining them to a context, which i think i was wrong in doing it.
&nbsp;

so my issue with psychology is that it may inform us about a posteriori "world of man", it may justify reward, punishment, etc within the subject (in psychological terms) it has no relation to the material world but only the subject reaction to it, it may ask questions about the whole of the individual experience (social, cultural, etc).
&nbsp;

we must use the social/natural sciences for being rational but its direct role only adds the complexity of the analysis of the subject.
&nbsp;

what i'm begging here is, to use the social/natural sciences to get to real data about the subject and use it for the rational pursuit and fulfillment of ones possible freedoms, and not to use the psychology as a tool for analysis of the pursuit of freedom directly.

&nbsp;
how do you see psychology playing a role in understanding freedom of will?

@caryoscelus: btw, one of the influences of Berdyaev was Kierkegaard, in him, his existentialist discussion of freedom is clearer (possibility and anxiety), concerning what inquisitions brought about this line of thinking, but the dialectical turn in Berdyaev, unlike Hegel, is not in the spiritual world anymore but in relation with nature itself. thus the psychology behind it is not part of the analysis but a tool for further inquisition in the process of realising freedom.
&nbsp;
a formalisation of terminology is needed then, i did not wanted to go further than accepting a mere distinction of freedom as possibility and as rationally realised, but that shipped has sailed.

